–Zesnulá","1145–Male":"1145–Zesnulý","about 1170":"okolo 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"okolo 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"da":{"about 1145–":"omkring 1145–Afdød","1145–Female":"1145–Afdød","1170–Female":"1170–Afdød","1145–Male":"1145–Afdød","about 1170":"omkring 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"omkring 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1145–":"circa 1145–Overleden","1145–Female":"1145–Overleden","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1145–Male":"1145–Overleden","about 1170":"circa 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"circa 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1145–":"about 1145–Deceased","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1145–Male":"1145–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"about 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cumming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): most probably a habitational name from Bosc-Benard-Commin in Eure, France. This place lies on the edge of the Forêt de Rouvray, near Rouen, in the heart of the district from which came numerous Domesday barons, and so is much more likely to be the source of the name than Comines in Nord. The name is also possibly derived from the personal name <i>Cumin</i>, which is found in Norfolk, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th and 13th centuries and may be of Breton origin, according to Reaney. Compare Old Breton <i>Cunmin</i>, which also appears as <i>Cumin</i>, and is from <i>con-</i> ‘hound’ with an uncertain second element, perhaps the <i>min</i> ‘edge’ which is found in other personal names.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cuimín</b> (or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>) ‘son (or ‘descendant’) of <i>Cuimín</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>cam</i> ‘crooked’. There was a 7th-century abbot of Iona named <i>Cumin</i>. In Scotland, this Irish surname became confused with the Norman name.","History: A notable bearer of the Norman surname is Wilhelmus Comyn, Bishop of Durham, who came north to Scotland with King David I in 1124 and was appointed Chancellor of Scotland. He established his nephew Richard in Tynedale and Roxburghshire, and Richard also rose to be Chancellor of Scotland. The Comyn or Cumming family gained the earldoms of Buchan and Menteith and rose to be the most powerful noble family in Scotland in the century before the rise of King Robert Bruce."],"variants":[{"name":"Cowman","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Cumming  ."]},{"name":"Coman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Romanian Vasile, Cornel, Mihaela, Nicolae, Sorin, Viorel.","Irish (Tipperary and Waterford): shortened form of <b>Mac Cuimín</b> or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>, see   Cumming  .","English (Norfolk): variant of   Common  ."]},{"name":"Cummings","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Cumming  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Common","meanings":["nickname from Middle English <i>comen</i>, Old English <i>cuman</i> ‘guest, stranger, newcomer’.","variant of   Cumming  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Cumming was born about 1145, in Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland. He had at least 1 daughter with Hexilda."},"et":{"about 1145–":"umbes 1145–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"umbes 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1145–":"noin 1145–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1145–Male":"1145–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"noin 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1145–":"environ 1145–Décédé","1145–Female":"1145–Décédée","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1145–Male":"1145–Décédé","about 1170":"environ 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"environ 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"William Cumming est né environ 1145, à Seton, Haddingtonshire, Écosse. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Hexilda."},"de":{"about 1145–":"um 1145–Verstorben","1145–Female":"1145–Verstorben","1170–Female":"1170–Verstorben","1145–Male":"1145–Verstorben","about 1170":"um 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"um 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","lifeSummary":"William Cumming wurde um 1145 in Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland geboren. Er hatte mit Hexilda mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1145–":"about 1145–Desede","1145–Female":"1145–Desede","1170–Female":"1170–Desede","1145–Male":"1145–Desede","about 1170":"about 1170","1145":"1145","about 1145":"about 1145","1170":"1170","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"hu":{"about 1145–":"1145 körül–elhunyt","1145–Female":"1145–elhuny